I think this is a misguided attempt at "security".  I have a similar
problem with another company here in sillicon valley, which refuses to
convert to domain naming because then everyone would be able to see the
names of their machines, which they are afraid will give away some kind
of trade secret (even though  their machines tend to have unimaginative
names like "sun1", "sun2", etc.).  They are already on the Internet, so
if anyone wanted to break into their machines they already could just
by specifying the IP number, but they continue with their single
gateway being XXX.ARPA and local /etc/hosts files!

Mostly we need to educate people that knowing a machine's name does not
change the security of that system.  Having an unlisted phone number
does not prevent crank phone calls.

	-- WIN

